titleStmt.title: Istanbul, Topkapı Palace Museum (Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi), "Saray 50395" (Gotthelf Bergsträßer archives) [= Karatay 40]

respStmt.resp: Edited by Michael Marx in collaboration with Tobias J. Jocham et. al. TEI version created by Yasmin Faghihi and Huw Jones

msIdentifier.repository: Topkapı Palace Museum (Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi) , Istanbul

summary.p: 363 (?) folios; Parchment; Shelfmark: "Saray 50395" (Gotthelf Bersträßer archives); Complete codex; 16 lines per page; Dimensions: 240 x 330 mm; Script style corresponds to kūfī D IV (typology of F. Déroche 1983, pp. 41-45 with the description of style D) with some variations, see palaeography by Salome Beridze; Estimated date of production: 750-900 (?).

Films with images ("Kasten F (Filme 01-11)" of Gotthelf-Bergsträßer-Archives) of this nearly complete codex were taken in Topkapi Sarayi Palace in the early 1930s, by Otto Pretzl, Gotthelf Bergsträßer or a third person. Unfortunately all images are blurry and their readability could not be improved. According to the photos, the codex appears to have 364 folios, the last of which being an ornamented page at the very end of the book, registered as fol. 364r in this entry. All Bergsträßer images show double pages of the opened codex; in this catalogue entry for each page, one image with the individual page (image no. 1) together with the initial photo of the opened codex (image no. 2) is given.

Bergsträßer's Geschichte des Qorans, table 5 ("Tafel V, Abbildung 6") contains an image of the opened codex, with the caption: "Istanbul, Saray 50395 Format der Seite 24 x 33 cm Sure 13,42-14,11". These two pages in Bergsträßer's book correspond to fol. 151v and fol. 152r in the assumed folio numbering of this entry. The manuscript corresponds to a Qurʾān listed under shelfmark "Y. 4571" (entry No. 40) in Fehmi Karatay's catalogue of the Topkapi library (p. 15): "40 Y. 4571 Mushaf Kur’an’dan bir yaprak. Parşömen, 240mm boy ve 325mm eninde 363 yaprak. Sahifede kufi yazı ile 255mm uzunl[uğunda]. 16 satır. Tahminen III. (IX) asırda istinsah edilmiştir. Baştan 3 ve sondan 6 sahifesi ile sure başları tezhiplidir. Y. 7, 347-351 sonradan yazılmıştır. Cildi tahta üzerine hendesi şekilde şemse ve köşelikli koyu kahve rengi deridir. Tam bir Kuran nushadır." Esra Gözeler and Tuba Karaşahin translate this entry as follows: "40 Y. 4571 Codex of the Qurʾān Parchment. 363 junk shaped leaves of 240 mm height and 325 mm width. The text area, written in Kufic script [contains] 16 lines measuring 255 mm. Probably copied during the 3rd (9th) century. 3 pages from the beginning and 6 pages from the end and the sūra beginnings are illuminated. L. 7, 347-351 were written later. The brown leather binding covered on wooden [board] has a mandorla (şemse) in geometric form and corner pieces. The codex is a complete one."

Karatay does not mention "50395" as call number, but "Y. 4571" a manuscript with similar dimensions, number of folios (363 fol. in Karatay against 364 fol. in Bergsträßer's archives), and the same number of lines to the page (sixteen). Karatay says that the first three and the last six folios have golden illuminations which seems to match with the available images of "50395" as well. According to the Turkish catalogue, folio 7 and folios 347 to 351 were written later, which corresponds to the available images which show a very different script style (see fol.7, fol. 347r, fol. 351v). Photos from Bergsträßer's archives of this codex do not contain pages of the replaced section, fol. 347v to fol. 351r, presumably because they were of lesser interest at the time.

The photos do not give folio numbers as other "Bergsträßer Qurʾān photos" usually contain them. The order of the images, especially those taken from the last pages of the codex (fol. 361 to fol. 364) needs to be verified by consulation of the original codex. In order to establish a preliminary numbering, information given by Karatay about folios 7, and fol. 347-351 has been used as "anchorpoints". Nevertheless, the given folio numbering remains doubtful, especially for the last four folios. The first folio of the original codex, with the beginning of surah 1 (Q 1,1-4) seems to missing, as the first availabe text page (fol. 1r), starts with Q 1, 5-7. An image of a preceding page, containing a dedication, an endowment or a colophon, is listed as fol. 0v.
As complete codices in kūfī D script style are rare, Bergsträßer's photos point us to an exceptional document that hopefully will be accessible and perhaps edited in the future.

Text ranges of the images have been idientified by Emaan Safah. The digitization of the images on films from Gotthelf Bergsträßer archives has been carried out by Tobias J. Jocham. Farah Cahya Artika has prepared the images for the data base. Esra Gözeler and Tuba Karaşahin have translated Fehmi Karatay's catalogue entry. Salome Beridze has described the paleography of this manuscript.

The script style of this manuscript is kūfī type D.IV (typology of François Déroche 1983, pp. 41-45 with the description of style D) with some variations. The ʾalif in the independent form has a shorter return at the base and a longer shaft than in D.IV. The letter is closer to the C.Ia style. The ʿain in the initial form has a hook that is larger and more open, which is closer to the D.I and D.III groups. When at the end of a word, the letter form is related to the B.I and B.II groups. The letter qāf in the independent and final forms resembles the D.I. The letters mīm and hāʾ are also related to the B.II group, being close to the D.I style at the same time. As for lām-ʾalif, the form is similar to the C.Ia or C.III groups. The fol. 7 has been replaced and is written in a different (later) script, as well as folio 347 recto and 351 verso. (Salome Beridze)
